<div id="review_75144663" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/75144663" />
    <a title="Nick Black" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/655723-nick-black"><img alt="Nick Black" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315018121p2/655723.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/75144663?book_show_action=true">Oct 20, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nick Black" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nick Black" href="/user/show/655723-nick-black">Nick Black</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655723-nick-black?shelf=likely-reread">likely-reread</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer75144663" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8762074613647888041">It had some really memorable lines, but overall I dug <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4191.The_Cold_Six_Thousand' title='The Cold Six Thousand by James Ellroy' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Cold Six Thousand</a> more. We&apos;ll see how <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6094181.Blood_s_A_Rover' title='Blood&apos;s A Rover by James Ellroy' rel='nofollow noopener'>Blood&apos;s a Rover</a> goes, but overall I&apos;m thinking James Ellroy is something I&apos;d enjoyed much more eight years ago. What&apos;s the <i>point</i>, Pete/Boyd/Wayne/Littell? For such multitalented, resourceful and industrious individuals, they sure seem to lack any meaningful <i>weltanschauung</i> of their own, content to play the part of vessels. Not a stride is broken upon the death of XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX late in this firs</span>
  <span id="freeText8762074613647888041" style="display:none">It had some really memorable lines, but overall I dug <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4191.The_Cold_Six_Thousand" title="The Cold Six Thousand by James Ellroy" rel="nofollow noopener">The Cold Six Thousand</a> more. We'll see how <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6094181.Blood_s_A_Rover" title="Blood's A Rover by James Ellroy" rel="nofollow noopener">Blood's a Rover</a> goes, but overall I'm thinking James Ellroy is something I'd enjoyed much more eight years ago. What's the <i>point</i>, Pete/Boyd/Wayne/Littell? For such multitalented, resourceful and industrious individuals, they sure seem to lack any meaningful <i>weltanschauung</i> of their own, content to play the part of vessels. Not a stride is broken upon the death of XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX late in this first book, knowing another untermensch will rise up from Ellroy's underworld miasma.<br /><br />And the formulaic, almost algorithmic nature! What percentage of (super-short, so you feel deliciously smart as you're chugging through them) chapters could be plotted in one line:<br /><br />{ Major character X momentary ally X minor character X ( brace | kill | twist!) }?<br /><br />Sure, the welling-up and breaking-down Reverse-Everyman is one of Ellroy's major points, but if you're going to talk about meanings and themes you must move into the realm of Serious Literature, which Mr. Ellroy decidedly is <i>not</i>.<br /><br />James Edgar Hoover as written by Ellroy is one of the most spectacular characters I've ever seen, though he benefits tremendously from foiling; one gets the feeling conversations with JEH, for all their trenchant brevity, consumed a majority of Ellroy's writing time (or were done in single drafts, either way -- as unforgettably recorded by Goodie Mob, "ain't no in-between you either off or on"). The Kennedys could have been more vividly painted had they been seen only through radio and television broadcasts; they're devices and nothing more. Pete has limitless promise, and could play the role of a Hagbard Celine, but he's confused more than anything. Confusion, though, is the vantage point least amenable to decisive action, the only action in which Pete engages. My engineer-self recoils in horror from what could otherwise be a sympathetic character.<br /><br />In the interests of full disclosure, I found myself regularly bewildered, scandalized, and finally dismissively annoyed by Ellroy's Deep South, populated exclusively by Klansmen, Cubans and Negroes (thankfully, he restricted himself mainly to dread Mississippi, indeed a blighted place). I've lived in Atlanta all my years, and in that time have seen Klan influence, or indeed the overt racial tension visible in parts of New York, Boston, Detroit and LA, only in the portrayals of fiction, prime time, and movies (and David Duke, but Louisiana is its own hellhole, for which the southeast accepts no responsibility. Blame Texas; blame France). I've no doubt things improved immeasurably since '70, especially in the rural areas, but really all any unfortunate inhabitant of the rural South ought be thinking about is How are we Getting to Atlanta?, When the Hell are we Leaving This Godforsaken Place?, Why Aren't we Departing Now?, and Where is the Nearest Chik-fil-a?<br /><br />----<br />Amazon 2009-10-20. Fiction must return to my life by the end of the year, and y'all rave on about this fellow like no one else.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8762074613647888041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


