  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_190671643" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/190671643" />
    <a title="Colin Miller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/739464-colin-miller"><img alt="Colin Miller" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442509875p2/739464.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/190671643?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Colin Miller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Colin Miller" href="/user/show/739464-colin-miller">Colin Miller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Those who can stand Ellroy's bent</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/739464-colin-miller?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer190671643" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9789404899306457383">James Ellroy’s <i>American Tabloid</i> may not be as good as <i>The Black Dahlia</i>, but it’s still an excellent, historically-based crime novel.<br/><br/>James Ellroy isn’t for everyone. It isn’t just his staccato neo-noir voice or his violent stories. He often writes characters that, at the very least, display racist and misogynistic tendencies. Ellroy himself has been accused of these very things and has responded in, well, <i>Ellroy-like</i> fashion (pretty much him insulting and cussing at people without really addressi</span>
  <span id="freeText9789404899306457383" style="display:none">James Ellroy’s <i>American Tabloid</i> may not be as good as <i>The Black Dahlia</i>, but it’s still an excellent, historically-based crime novel.<br /><br />James Ellroy isn’t for everyone. It isn’t just his staccato neo-noir voice or his violent stories. He often writes characters that, at the very least, display racist and misogynistic tendencies. Ellroy himself has been accused of these very things and has responded in, well, <i>Ellroy-like</i> fashion (pretty much him insulting and cussing at people without really addressing the issue). Make no mistake, Ellroy <i>is</i> messed up. The murder of his mother in his youth has shaped both his work and his taste in women; so again, I don’t fault anyone who can’t connect with this type of material.<br /><br />If you can though, <i>American Tabloid</i> is rich and deep. The novel covers the historical U.S. events of November 1958 to November 1963 and essentially writes in three main fictional characters to shape the key events during that time. They include: former Los Angeles deputy turned private eye/crime associate Pete Bondurant; southern FBI agent Kemper Boyd; and FBI agent (and friend/former partner of Kemper Boyd) Ward Littell. All three work for and against various historical figures—including Jimmy Hoffa, J. Edgar Hoover, John and Robert Kennedy, Howard Hughes—and with and against each other, depending on what fits their needs. Like other Ellroy works, these three men go through changes in power and personality, and the appeal is seeing where they’ll end up by the novel’s end. Unlike <i>The Black Dahlia</i>—which I think benefits from stronger relationships between fewer characters—<i>American Tabloid</i> ties in political agendas of large organizations including the mafia, the FBI, the CIA, Fidel Castro’s communist regime, and the White House itself. Conspiracies run amok, and Ellroy crams so much plot and so many twists into the pages that I doubt even he can keep it straight, but it’s entertaining enough that you roll with the confusion.<br /><br />My favorite character has to be comedian turned informant, Lenny Sands. Unlike the main characters that seem to be written as a tad too resilient (even if they do get broken down from time to time), Lenny Sands has secrets and manipulations from which he can’t escape. He’s probably top 10 character material for me if not higher. However, as consistently good as <i>American Tabloid</i> is, sometimes Ellroy gets stuck in his little loops and ruts. More than once, there were pages full of nothing but repetitive two-line paragraphs, several people get slapped and swallow teeth like it’s no big thing, and in the end, Ellroy writes a key plot point that doesn’t make sense. Remember, this is a book where characters and allegiances shift constantly, so it takes Ellroy being way far off base for me to call him out on it. Despite these flaws, American Tabloid holds up well over its near-600 pages, and much like his L.A. quartet series, I plan on continuing on with this Underworld USA trilogy. Three stars and reaching higher. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9789404899306457383" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

